Share of Maximum Active Power that can be committed to Automatic Frequency Restoration Reserve by a typical power plant generating electricity from wind energy (on- and offshore)

unit

Available Secondary Energy|Electricity
unit
['EJ/yr', 'GWh']
description
Total net potential electricity production this is equivalent to the total electricity mix capacity multiplied by the number of hours in the period multiplied by the maximum achievable load factor this is also equivalent to the Secondary Energy if all the generation assets would produce at maximum capacity during the period

description
Operation Cost of (REEV) Electric vehicle that also includes a generator (extender) whose function is to use gas to output electric energy to the motor when the electric power in the battery is to low. The range extender does not drive the vehicle directly. units

Reserve|Electricity|Replacement
unit
MW
description
Replacement reserve (RR) means the active power reserves available to restore or support the required level of frequency restoration reserve (FRR) to be prepared for additional system imbalances, including generation reserves.
Reserve|Electricity|Requirement|Manual Frequency Restoration
unit
MW
description
Manual frequency restoration reserve (mFRR) is used to relieve the automatic frequency restoration reserve during prolonged imbalances.

unit
['MWh', 'GWh']
description
Energy spillage that could not be stored by a all batteries unit. Several energy models include spillage variables related to renewable energy production; however, another way is to include a spillage variable to the all batteries unit since it is the last sink of the power network

Spillage|Electricity|Electric Vehicle|Range extended
unit
['MWh', 'GWh']
description
Energy spillage that could not be stored by a (REEV) Electric vehicle that also includes a generator (extender) whose function is to use gas to output electric energy to the motor when the electric power in the battery is to low. The range extender does not drive the vehicle directly. unit. Several energy models include spillage variables related to renewable energy production; however, another way is to include a spillage variable to the (REEV) Electric vehicle that also includes a generator (extender) whose function is to use gas to output electric energy to the motor when the electric power in the battery is to low. The range extender does not drive the vehicle directly. unit since it is the last sink of the power network
